We decided to give this highly rated place a try. The long line outside did not deter our decision, we see it as a great sign. We waited nearly 35 min, it's really not too bad for a busy place in the city. Since we had enough time during the wait to look at the menu, we ordered immediately when we sat down. 25 min went by, another table sat down next to us. They also put in their order right away. In less than 5 min, their gumbo came out. We ordered gumbo too and wondered if it had been forgotten. We waited for the server to come around to inquire, but he didn't. Few more minutes later, the same table next to us was served their full lunch and we were still twirling our thumbs. By this time, I got up to ask our server about our order. In his unapologetic, condescending tone he replied, "we'll get your food baby! It's only food, nothing to get excited about baby!" So, while there are few thousands of restaurants in SF to choose for brunch, we chose your place, which served "nothing to get excited about"!?? And DO NOT call me "baby"! By this time, the wait was not even the issue anymore. We've waited longer at other busy restaurants. But his condescending tone fired me up, we were ready to walk out! He came around later offering different explanations, first, it was that our order was more difficult (we ordered straight off the menu with no modifications) then later, he explained that "the chef apologizes, there was a big confusion in the kitchen". Both explanations (true or not), would have been gladly accepted at the beginning. But they came way too late! The food: Our gumbo came out with a dirty spoon. We asked for a new one, which never came. We ate it with our forks. We ordered the pull-pork Benedict and pork belly with cheese grits. Other than the grits, which was really good, nothing else was worth the rave and definitely not worth the rude service. We originally looked fwd to ordering the beignets, but no...just no. Couldn't try to get out of there fast enough! To the owner: even if you did have the best food in town, no customer should have to endure this kind of treatment. We know that losing a customer or two won't hurt your pocket, but does your server have to make it so obvious!? We will never be back! There are too many humble restaurants we need to try.

The photos of Brenda's food don't look as if they're all that much but the dishes I had were among the most well-executed. The only other experience I've had with cajun/creole cuisine is Toulouse Petit, which is the Seattle equivalent of Brenda's, except Toulouse is like the chewed up, second-hand crusted cum sock of Brenda's. It's sadly the pitiful truth. From what I tasted, from their oyster flight to staples like jambalaya and red beans and rice, Brenda's deserves each and every star they have received. Best of all is that they don't cajole you into eating at their place with insincere service and a hard-to-read menu. This is a very low-key, intimate restaurant that we almost missed had we not noticed an employee walk in from his break. They give you roasted black eyed peas upon being seated. At each and every table, and granted that this place is small and cramped, there are napkins, forks, knives, and sauces that you can freely use at your disposal. I chose their chicken and andouille sausage jambalaya off their chalkboard filled with other miscellaneous specials. I would not be startled to learn that their recipes have been passed down for generations down an incestuous family line. Now they're using their food as the gateway for indoctrinating people like me to believe that seeking all-encompassing autonomy and monogamous relationships is meaningless compared to becoming one of Brenda's sister wives and uprearing an army of toddlers. Conspiracies aside, although I wouldn't object, their food is ridiculously good and for a modest price. The rice in the jambalaya was cooked and seasoned perfectly with pieces of chicken and sausage scattered throughout that gave it a good punch. It came with a side of green salad, not overly dressed, to off-set the spiciness and heaviness. It wasn't a sad glop of rice set on a stone pan. The presentation was clean and served simply on a white plate. I like the philosophy of letting the food speak for itself. For dessert, I insisted on ordering the bananas foster bread pudding. Neither my partner nor I prefer sweets, yet it was the perfect amount of sweetness with slices of bananas that were cooked thoroughly enough that the whole dessert remained the same temperature. It's not creative but it was very well-done. I think the dessert portion is perfect for two. Paired with a couple glasses of wine and I am a happy camper. Service, albeit a little confusing because we had two women switch off serving us, exceeded expectations with what I would expect from Brenda's. I never had to wave down a waitress because they regularly visited our table to check up on us, which is quite the opposite of my usual experience, as I am far from the complacent doormat of a customer. If you can get here before the dinner rush, I think this is an all around solid place for dinner. For restaurants with smaller menus, there's really no room for mishaps.

    The photos of Brenda's food don't look as if they're all that much but the dishes I had were among the most well-executed.  The only other experience I've had with cajun/creole cuisine is Toulouse Petit, which is the Seattle equivalent of Brenda's, except Toulouse is like the chewed up, second-hand crusted cum sock of Brenda's.  It's sadly the pitiful truth.

    From what I tasted, from their oyster flight to staples like jambalaya and red beans and rice, Brenda's deserves each and every star they have received.  Best of all is that they don't cajole you into eating at their place with insincere service and a hard-to-read menu.  This is a very low-key, intimate restaurant that we almost missed had we not noticed an employee walk in from his break.  They give you roasted black eyed peas upon being seated.  At each and every table, and granted that this place is small and cramped, there are napkins, forks, knives, and sauces that you can freely use at your disposal.  

    I chose their chicken and andouille sausage jambalaya off their chalkboard filled with other miscellaneous specials.  I would not be startled to learn that their recipes have been passed down for generations down an incestuous family line.  Now they're using their food as the gateway for indoctrinating people like me to believe that seeking all-encompassing autonomy and monogamous relationships is meaningless compared to becoming one of Brenda's sister wives and uprearing an army of toddlers.

    Conspiracies aside, although I wouldn't object, their food is ridiculously good and for a modest price.  The rice in the jambalaya was cooked and seasoned perfectly with pieces of chicken and sausage scattered throughout that gave it a good punch.  It came with a side of green salad, not overly dressed, to off-set the spiciness and heaviness.  It wasn't a sad glop of rice set on a stone pan.  The presentation was clean and served simply on a white plate.  I like the philosophy of letting the food speak for itself.

    For dessert, I insisted on ordering the bananas foster bread pudding.  Neither my partner nor I prefer sweets, yet it was the perfect amount of sweetness with slices of bananas that were cooked thoroughly enough that the whole dessert remained the same temperature.  It's not creative but it was very well-done.  I think the dessert portion is perfect for two.  Paired with a couple glasses of wine and I am a happy camper.

    Service, albeit a little confusing because we had two women switch off serving us, exceeded expectations with what I would expect from Brenda's.  I never had to wave down a waitress because they regularly visited our table to check up on us, which is quite the opposite of my usual experience, as I am far from the complacent doormat of a customer.

    If you can get here before the dinner rush, I think this is an all around solid place for dinner.  For restaurants with smaller menus, there's really no room for mishaps.

The shrimp were well-cooked and flavorful-and definitely enough. I couldn't finish my plate, but I also had one of their delicious biscuits. The biscuits are really worth it. I saw they sell those frozen. I am sad I didn't get to try the chicken or the collard greens, being a soul food fan. It was very good overall.

    Yes please!

    I was on vacation and dined here with a few friends. We came on a Saturday evening and signed in via chalkboard. The wait for a table of 3 was about 30-40 mins. It's a relatively small restaurant, but very cool hip decor. The wall of mirrors really caught my eyes.

    PARKING: Street

    Appetizer:
    -Crawfish Beighnet $3 each: Man, so good! I have to end it there. Filled inside with crawfish that's marinated and topped outside with cayenne, scallion and cheddar.

    Entrees:
    -Catfish des Allemands $16.75: This entree was delicious. The catfish was bronzed and filet. Soft and tasty. It really stood out and had good sides, which were crawfish etoufee and pecan rice pilaf.
    -BBQ Pork Ribs $15.75: Very tasty and bold flavors for the ribs. Not overly powered by the BBQ sauce  that's glazed and has a smokey taste, which is a definite must have for ribs. It was accompanied with mac 'n' cheese and collard greends. Southern it was.
    -Braised Pork Shoulders $17-18: This entree was a special my friend ordered. It came with green beans and mashed potatoes. It was delish. The pork shoulder chunks were very tender yet slightly chewy to taste. Kind of overpriced in my opinion, but it was worth it.

    Overall, great food. Service was great during my visit with friends. Wish we had one in Georgia, but we have tons of Southern-style restaurants here.
